<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: RESEDA; HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL PLANNED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MANNING 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city's "Hazmobile" will visit Reseda beginning Thursday as part of the 
Bureau of Sanitation's household hazardous waste collection program. 
</P>
<P>
 People are asked to make appointments for hazardous-waste disposal by calling 
the hot line at (800) 98-TOXIC, or (800) 988-6942, said Jackie David, the 
bureau's public information director. 
</P>
<P>
 Callers will then be told where to take the materials, she said. They also 
will be sent a map to direct them to the collection center. 
</P>
<P>
 Appointments can be scheduled between 9 a.m. and 3 p.m., David said. 
</P>
<P>
 In Reseda, appointments can be scheduled on Thursday, Friday and Saturday and 
Dec. 1-3. 
</P>
<P>
 By law, motorists are not allowed to transport in their vehicles more than a 
five-gallon container, or more than 50 pounds of hazardous waste, she said. The 
so-called Hazmobile transports the materials for disposal. 
</P>
<P>
 The Hazmobile program is part of a countywide effort co-sponsored by the Los 
Angeles County Department of Public Works. 
</P>
<P>
 Among wastes that are considered hazardous are paint, motor oil, pesticides, 
cleaners and other common household materials labeled toxic, corrosive or 
flammable liquids and poisons, David said. The collections are conducted to 
prevent people from disposing of the materials illegally, such as by dumping 
them in sewers, she said. FRANK MANNING 
</P>
</TEXT>
