EAST VALLEY FOCUS: VAN NUYS; 'GIVING TREE' TO BENEFIT HIV PATIENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAKI BECKER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 To offer a little holiday cheer to San Fernando Valley residents infected with 
HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, and others affected by it, the Valley HIV/AIDS 
Center will team up with a Thrifty Drug Store in Van Nuys for a two-part 
project.  
</P>
<P>
 A Christmas tree, adorned with cards imprinted with the names of children who 
are HIV-positive or have parents who are HIV-positive, will be set up at the 
Thrifty store. 
</P>
<P>
 Patrons will be asked to pick one of the cards and buy a gift for the child. 
</P>
<P>
 "The parents have spent so much money on medication that there's not enough 
left to buy toys for the kids," said Ana Vargas, a representative of the 
center. 
</P>
<P>
 Case managers who work directly with families affected by the virus are 
gathering names of children for inclusion on what Vargas called the "giving 
tree." 
</P>
<P>
 The second part of the project is a gift-wrapping booth that will be set up 
the last week before Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
 Valley Center volunteers will gift-wrap presents at the store for a $4 
donation to benefit the center. MAKI BECKER 
</P>
