<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY BRIEFLY: PACIFIC MUTUAL, CONNECTICUT FIRM MERGE, RAISE $83 
MILLION IN SALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a move creating the nation's fourth-largest publicly traded money 
management company, Pacific Mutual Life Insurance Co. and four of its 
subsidiaries on Tuesday finalized a previously announced merger with Thomson 
Advisory Group L.P. of Stamford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, the newly formed company, Pimco Advisors L.P., raised more than 
$83 million Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange by selling a minority stake 
of the new company to the public, which now owns 18% of Pimco Advisors.The 
Newport Beach mutual fund operator has $71 billion in customer assets. 
</P>
<P>
 Deteriorating market conditions Tuesday forced underwriters to downscale the 
planned offering to 4.6 million units -- about half of the 9.3 million units 
planned when the sale was announced last month. 
</P>
<P>
 Managers of Pimco Advisors reduced the size of the offering because the sale 
price was too low, according to William S. Thompson, a managing director at 
Pimco. The price of Pimco Advisors fell 11% to $18.125 per unit Tuesday from 
$20.375 when the sale was announced in October. The transaction involved the 
sale of partnership units instead of shares of common stock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
